
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Assessment of Ethical Performance of Organization Members: A Conceptual Framework
AU  - Gatewood, Robert D.
AU  - Carroll, Archie B.
Y1  - 1991/10/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1991.4279610
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1991.4279610
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 667
EP  - 690
VL  - 16
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article describes a conceptual framework that facilitates the assessment of the ethical performance of organization members. Based upon measurement principles applied to general work performance assessment, this framework is comprised of three components: the major stakeholders of the organization, the categorizing of organization members into individual or group units for accountability, and the division of performance into behaviors or results. Ethical standards can be formulated for combinations of these three components and expressed in terms of existing laws, or organizational or professional standards. The importance of the framework for business ethics research and theory development is discussed.
AB  - This article describes a conceptual framework that facilitates the assessment of the ethical performance of organization members. Based upon measurement principles applied to general work performance assessment, this framework is comprised of three components: the major stakeholders of the organization, the categorizing of organization members into individual or group units for accountability, and the division of performance into behaviors or results. Ethical standards can be formulated for combinations of these three components and expressed in terms of existing laws, or organizational or professional standards. The importance of the framework for business ethics research and theory development is discussed.
