TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Seasons of a CEO's Tenure
AU  - Hambrick, Donald C.
AU  - Fukutomi, Gregory D. S.
Y1  - 1991/10/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1991.4279621
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1991.4279621
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 719
EP  - 742
VL  - 16
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article proposes a model of the dynamics of the CEO's tenure in office. The central argument is that there are discernible phases, or seasons, within an executive's tenure in a position, and that these seasons give rise to distinct patterns of executive attention, behavior, and, ultimately, organizational performance. The five delineated seasons are (a) response to mandate, (b) experimentation, (c) selection of an enduring theme, (d) convergence, and (e) dysfunction. The theoretical and practical implications of the model are discussed.
AB  - This article proposes a model of the dynamics of the CEO's tenure in office. The central argument is that there are discernible phases, or seasons, within an executive's tenure in a position, and that these seasons give rise to distinct patterns of executive attention, behavior, and, ultimately, organizational performance. The five delineated seasons are (a) response to mandate, (b) experimentation, (c) selection of an enduring theme, (d) convergence, and (e) dysfunction. The theoretical and practical implications of the model are discussed.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1991.4279621
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1991.4279621
Y2  - 2026/04/24
